The paper deals with information-theoretic limits of community detection, which is a problem in information theory and machine learning. Therefore, cs.IT (Information Theory) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also deals with the stochastic block model, which is a popular model in network science and graph theory, making cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) a likely sub-category as well. The paper provides upper and lower bounds on the proportion of community labels recovered, which involves combinatorial and probabilistic arguments, making cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) a possible sub-category. The paper also deals with the sparse setting, which involves analyzing the behavior of the model as the number of nodes grows large, making cs.LG (Machine Learning) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with the limits of community detection, which involves analyzing the performance of algorithms and models, making cs.SD (Software Engineering) a possible sub-category.
